<font color="#FF0000">AT WHAT COST TO BE AMERICAN?</font><br>
<tt>Sat Apr 19 19:11:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
The following took place about forty years ago. I wrote it not to long ago for an e-mail friend. As such, to the best I can recollect, everything is accurate with no pontifications, elaborations or exagerations. In other words, no bullshit.<br><br>
When I was nine, I got my first real job as a paperboy.  At this time, I lived in Kailua.  However, there was no mass transit system to speak of in those days.  My paper route was on the other side of the Island (Kalihi) as there no routes available in my area.  There was, however, a<br>
&quot;gitney&quot; service, that consisted of large, old cars that could seat about nine people.  It cost seventy-five cents each way and they would drop us off downtown, Honolulu.  From there, I would catch a bus to Kalihi.  I had a bike that I left at the house where my papers were dropped off.  I had prearranged for the gitney service to pick me up a<br>
block from school, make the trip to Honolulu, catch the bus to Kalihi, fold my papers, deliver them, catch the bus back to Honolulu, catch the gitney which delivered me to my house.  By the time I got home, it would be about seven p.m..<br><br>
At that time, Kalihi was mostly a Japanese community.  The people who lived there were from poor to lower middle class. But no matter how small or old the homes, they were kept imacculate.  The houses were clean, inside and out and the small yards were well groomed.<br><br>
One of my customers was an elderly gentleman by the name of Mr. Fujihara.  He was isei (first generation; second generation is nisei). He spoke relatively decent english and was always polite to me.  When I would collect for the paper, standing in the doorway, I could see that his house was sparsely furnished, but as I mentioned before,everything<br>
he had was well kept.  He also lived alone.<br><br>
One day, on a Saturday, I was collecting for the paper, and when I reached his house, his door was open though the screen door was shut and his car was there.  I called out his name and decided to see if he was in the backyard.  I walked around through his carport to the backyard. <br>
From the house to his border, the strip of land consisted of only ten feet, (not uncommon in Hawaii, land is at a premium) and he had poured a concrete slab over the entire area.  He had a hot house type of covering over the slab to filter the sunlight, but left the sides open.  He had<br>
built a work area where he kept bags of potting soil, fertilizers, hand garden tools and lots of potted plants were occupying most of the concrete slab.  He was working, planting seeds in small pots, when he saw me.  When I told him why I was there, he brushed dirt from his hands, and went inside to get the money.  While he was gone, I went to<br>
look at the seeds.  Off to the side, there was a large gunney sack of these same seeds.  He then came out and handed me three quarters.  I asked him what kind of seeds these were, and he told me that these seeds were norfolk pine and the seeds came from the Island of Lanai.  He<br>
explained that norfolk pine seedlings were in big demand in Japan, therefore he would grow the seedlings and ship them to Japan. He proceeded to show me a bunch of seedlings that he said were ready to be readied for shipping.  I guess I showed some interest, because he asked me if I wanted to help him.  I said o.k., and he told me to come back next weekend.<br><br>
The next Saturday, I got there as early as I could.  He showed me how to remove the seedling from the pots, prepare the roots so they wouldn't get shocked, then wrapped the roots with newspaper and tie them.  Each one I did, he would quietly examine the job I did, then place the into what I figured was the shipping container.  After we did about two<br>
hundred, he taught me how to prepare a potting soil mix to plant seeds. The rest of the day, thats what we did.  He provided a small lunch for me, though, he himself didn't eat.  About three in the afternoon, he sent me away.  He thanked me for my help and told me I could come back<br>
anytime.<br><br>
For about six months, this was how I spent my Saturdays.  One day, while working, I asked if I could use his bathroom. I then walked in, turn down the hallway and looked for the bathroom.  Before I got to it, I peered into an opened doorway to a room.  The only funiture was a homemade stool in the center of the room.  I could see that the walls<br>
were covered with framed and unframed photographs, letters, newspapeer cliipings, etc..  Curiosity got the best of me and I stepped inside the room.  All four walls were covered except in a corner was a small Buddist shrine.  I went to a wall and after looking at the items on the wall, I realized that it contained his family history, so I tried to find the beginning of his story.<br><br>
It started on the left side of the shrine when he got married to a girl while in Japan.  There were photographs of the wedding, and pictures of him and his wife where I assumed they spent there honeymoon in Japan. It occured to me that this was pre-war Japan from the dates I saw on<br>
documents.  The wall went on to show them having two sons about two years apart.  Then their exodus to Hawaii. Citizenship papers. Pictures showed a house, their kids, growing up, going to school, report cards, sports awards, etc..  Then newspaper articles about Pearl Harbor.  There<br>
were articles about Japanese-Americans being relocated to camps on the mainland.  Then there were pictures of his family in a camp that I think may have been in Arizona.  There were I.D. cards and other papers related to this internment camp.  Then newspaper articles about the<br>
formation of the &quot;Japanese-American&quot; military unit (442nd Division), and papers showing that his sons volunteered along with pictures of his sons in uniform.  There were medals and campaign ribbons on the wall along with letters from his sons while in Europe.  Newspaper accounts of<br>
military activity in Europe led me to believe this was how he tracked where his sons went. Then hospital papers documenting his wife pregnancy and pictures of her pregnant. <br><br>
The wall then showed two telegrams from the army informing him that one son was killed in action and the other was missing in action.  The dates of these telegrams were about one month apart.  Then there was a what looked like a camp newspaper article written about the wife and child dying from complications of the pregnacy.  There the story ended, on the right hand side of the shrine.<br><br>
I had read all four walls.  I looked towards the doorway, and he was standing there.  He turned from me, then went back outside.  I looked at the walls again, then followed him.  We worked for a couple more hours before going home.  He didn't mention anything about my intrusion into his privacy, only of the job on hand.  In fact, the entire time that I knew him, all we talked about were about the seedlings.  Talking was at a minimum.<br><br>
I was afraid that he wouldn't have me back again after that day, but he indicated that he would see me the next week.  For the next couple of months, I wanted to ask him about that room, but didn't know how.  He never volunteered anything.<br><br>
One afternoon, while delivering papers, I stopped by to confirm that I would be there the following Saturday.  Through the screen door, it appeared that he was asleep sitting at his dinette table.  I called to him, he didn't answer.  I went inside, and it was obvious that he had<br>
died.  I went to inform the man next door, he came and checked, then he called the police.  After giving my statement to the police, I finished my route, and went home.
